\section{Introduction}

The pressure on global water resources is intensifying as a result of population growth and demographic changes combined with climate change and an associated increase in climate variability \citep{}. Hence, achieving the equitable provision of freshwater to support human livelihoods and well-being while ensuring the continued function of ecosystems and environment is a defining challenge of our age \citep{poff_sustainable_2016}. Water management is broadly defined as a set of activities related to the ``storage, abstraction and redistribution'' of water from various sources to meet a wide range of human resource demands \citep{nazemi_inclusion_2015}. Achieving sustainable and resilient water systems requires a systems approach \citep{kasprzyk_defining_2018}. This paper presents a novel approach to representing human processes and interactions within... \\

Modelling is fundamental to the hydrological sciences \citep{buytaert_why_2008}. From an operational perspective, models provide a representation of the hydrology of a catchment or other geographical entity in order to forecast its response to future conditions or to simulate the behaviour of catchments where no output or state variables are measures \citep{beven_modelling_2001}. Perhaps more fundamentally, models represent hypotheses about aspects of system behaviour and may be viewed as part of a learning process \citep{hrachowitz_decade_2013}. Historically, much progress has been made in the representation of physical processes in hydrological models \citep[e.g.][]{}. More recently, hydrological models have been extended to represent human processes such as land use change and intensification, water management activities \citep{nazemi_inclusion_2015}. Catchment scale models such as SWAT, as well as global to regional scale models (PCR-GLOBWB, Community Water Model, H08). However, these models typically include the various results of human activities (e.g. water use in different sectors, land use change) as boundary conditions to the model. In reality, however, the human system and water system are inherently interlinked. A watershed model may be thought of as a basin-scale Earth system model \citep{li_watershed_2018}. The purpose of such models is twofold. First, they provide insight into the watershed system; second, they are used operationally to facilitate integrated river basin management \citep{}. Development of watershed models initially focused on improving the representation of physical processes. A major challenge in the development of watershed system models is to represent the co-evolution of human-water systems \citep{reid_earth_2010}.\\

To the extent that human processes are included in models of physical systems, the conventional approach has been to force models with the physical manifestation of socioeconomic change (e.g. changes in land use or water demand). Similarly, models of human processes, such as land use change, treat physical constraints, such as water availability, as boundary conditions \citep{li_watershed_2018}. In both cases, therefore, the various states of the opposing system are treated as exogenous variables which do not co-evolve \citep{}. Socio-hydrology... Various approaches to socio-hydrological modelling have been presented. Physical processes are usually represented in a simple way. For example, several models have explored irrigation water use... Crop yield determines farm income. Groundwater is often represented using a one-dimensional conceptual model (i.e. ignoring lateral groundwater flow). More complex aspects of the system are modelled using empirical relationships \citep{}. Society is modelled in numerous ways... \citep{mostert_alternative_2018}. Bottom-up approaches seek to develop system behaviour through the explicit representation of process in the physical and societal domain. On the other hand, top-down approaches examine the system outcomes and attempt to identify causal relationships which between variables in order to determine how a system responds to change \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. A common criticisim of top-down approaches is their inability to disaggregate system-level outcomes and provide information which is relevant to individuals \citep{}. \\

While the concepts which underlie socio-hydrology have existed in various guises for some decades \citep[e.g.][]{falkenmark_???_1998}, for various reasons such as the inherent complexity of coupled, co-evolutionary systems as well as inadequate means of dealing with the associated epistomological uncertainties, the feedbacks between human-water systems have not traditionally been included in models which seek to make predictions or inform policy \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. At least partly... this may originate from the strong focus on hydrological modelling as a predictive tool... with a focus on calibration and validation against observred hydrological outputs. However, the notion of hydrological modelling as a learning process has gained acceptance in the community... Hence, numerical modelling has emerged as an important mode of inquiry to advance our understanding of socio-hydrological systems \citep{}. A notable contribution was made by \citet{pande_sociohydrological_2016}, who explored the socio-hydrology of smallholder agriculture in Maharashtra, India, in relation to farmer distress.\\

The development of socio-hydrology has so far followed a \textit{positivist} approach which focuses on... In contrast, much of the research in water resources is \textit{normative}, or problem-focussed, with less emphasis on elucidating... \citep{pande} \\

