For the most part, existing quantitative socio-hydrological models consist of coupled, non-linear differential equations \citep{}. They tend to focus on the temporal dynamics of coupled human-water systems \citep{pande_progress_2017}. Consequently they are either spatially lumped or semi-distributed \citep{}. Several models consist of of stylized relationships which are intended to develop hypotheses about the system and explore its behaviour under different scenarios of social and environmental change \citep{van_emmerik_socio-hydrologic_2014,di_baldassarre_debates-perspectives_2015,garcia_question_2016}. Low dimensional models have proven adept at highlighting the aggregated response of a system to change, but they are unable to model the distribution of the response in the physical and social realms \citep{srinivasan_prediction_2016}. These models are useful in order to highlight data gaps (both in terms of temporal and spatial coverage of conventional variables, as well as variables which provide insight into the relationship between human-water systems but which have not previously been monitored) \citep{di_baldassarre_debates-perspectives_2015}. However, in the context of agricultural systems, which are often spatially extensive, such models are ill suited to exploring the co-evolution of agricultural sector and catchment hydrology with respect to processes which occur at larger spatial scales (such as food security). Moreover, the aggregate response of the social realm to changes in the physical system often poorly translate to insights which are relevant to individuals. \\

Conceptually, decision-making may be considered as a stepwise process. Analytical farmers formulate quantitative goals and use calculations to assess the likely consequences of the various options in order to select the optimal decision. On the other hand, intuitive farmers set intuitive goals, which are often directional in nature (e.g. an increase in yield), based on their experience, available reference points and other types of auxillary data \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. There are a range of theories about decision making, many of which are included in models of coupled human-environment systems \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. However, many models are based on expected utility, and hence assume that humans make rational decisions and are ``able to choose the optimal outcome considering all possible combinations based on perfect information \citep{koelher_???_2008}''. Howver, for various reasons humans do not make perfect decisions \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. It is therefore essential to involve decision makers during model conceptualisation in order to identify the imperatives which guide their decision-making process and the range of options they have available. \\

