As a result, there is a need to incorporate more realistic models capable of providing insight into socio-hydrological systems rather than simply reinforcing what is already known \citep{troy_debates-perspectives_2015,loucks_debates-perspectives_2015,blair_socio-hydrological_2016}, as well as making predictions about the co-evolution of social and hydrological systems under future conditions. This will involve more complete models of human behaviour \citep{loucks_debates-perspectives_2015}, as well as more accurate models of hydrological systems \citep{gober_debates-perspectives_2015,mount_data-driven_2016}. In order to simulate the magnitude and direction of change in system state variables it is necessary to accurately capture the underlying hydrological processes, such as river discharge, groundwater dynamics and root zone hydrology \citep{}. Earth system models now include water management activities such as ``irrigation schemes, reservoir operations and groundwater pumping'' \citep{voisin_effects_2017}. However, while there has been substantial progress in  To the extent that human processes are included in such models, the conventional approach has been to force models with the physical manifestation of socioeconomic change (e.g. changes in land use or water demand). Hence, this class of model is rarely capable of simulating the co-evolution of physical and social systems. \\

The dynamics of agricultural catchments has proved a major area of inquiry in socio-hydrological research \citep{}, and a wide variety of models have been developed to gain insight into agricultural systems \citep[e.g.][]{}. Broadly, these fall into two... The first of these takes a top-down approach... \citep{konar...}. The second looks at individual farms. In agricultural catchments, spatial heterogeneity in access to resources is a major determinant of wellbeing \citep{}. For example, farmers situated near the headwaters of a canal system tend to have a more reliable water source for irrigation than those farmers at the tail \citep{}. Moreover, incorporating a spatially explicit modelling approach may lead to a better representation of the underlying hydrology \citep{}. At the same time, the spatial and temporal dynamics of water availability is an important boundary condition to human activities such as food and energy production \citep{}, urbanisation and the management of urban systems \citep{}. \\

A number of methodological issues arise. ``...both the natural system and human dimension are reduced to fit in a quantitative model''. As \citet{wesselink_socio-hydrology_2017} point out, ``humans differ from other constituents of socio-hydrological models because they can choose how to act on their perception and preferences...''. One approach to dealing with this heterogeneity is to split populations into categories according to particular attributes which are relevant for the field of study. For example, \citet{srinivasan_hydrologic_2010}... Representing heterogeneity in populations in sufficient detail is a problem commonly encountered in computational ecology... Where possible, agent-based models are often used \citep[e.g.][]{}. However, in some situations this becomes computationally infeasible. The super-individual approach... \citep{}. \\

% Paragraph 5: What does this paper contribute?
To address the identified research gaps, we develop a farmer decision model for simulating farmer behaviour with respect to decisions about irrigation and farm investment of farmer and integrate this with a gridded regional hydrological model representing the surface and subsurface domains. We use the coupled model to explore the socio-hydrology of the Indo-Gangetic Plain, a region which is representative of many of the water management challenges we face today, particularly with respect to human-environment competition for water resources. The framework has been developed using a ``bottom-up'' approach, using field-level observations to define a range of plausible actions that a farmer may decide to implement... in response to various biophysical and socioeconomic state variables. The regional hydrological model consists of ... modules representing surface water hydrology and crop production, river and canal routing and two-dimensional groundwater dynamics, allowing us to explore the co-evolution of the human and hydrological system in space and time. The farmer decision model simulates the water management decisions of farmers in response to the various biophysical and socioeconomic state variables, mediating the flow of information between the models.\\

