The Indo-Gangetic Plain... Rainfall across the region is highly season, with around 80\% of the total annual rainfall falling during the south-west monsoon \citep{}. Water resources of the Indo-Gangetic Plain are groundwater dominated. Analysis of stable isotopes showed a high degree of conductivity between groundwater and surface water... ; a finding which is consistent with similar analyses carried out in the region \citep[e.g.][]{bonsor,joshi_tracing_2018}. The Ganga river and its tributaries provide important habitats for culturally important yet critically endangered species such as the Gharial crocodile and the Ganges river dolphin \citep{}, as well as supporting the livelihoods of inland fishing communities, which are among India's most marginalised \citep{nachiket?}. \\

Land use in the highly fertile Indo-Gangetic Plain is dominated by agriculture \citep{shah_is_2009}. This has been the case for at least 2000 years \citep{}; however, a step change in agricultural productivity occurred following India's green revolution and the introduction of high-yielding crop varieties. While rainfed agriculture is possible during the \textit{kharif} season, irrigation provides a valuable buffer against inter- and intra-annual variability and, furthermore, allows farmers to grow additional crops during the \textit{rabi} and \textit{zaid} seasons. Prior to the green revolution, farmers largely relied on the extensive colonial-era canal network \citep{shah}, but the influx of relatively low cost diesel pumps to the market in the mid-1970s allowed farmers to access the underlying aquifer with private tubewells, precipitating a rapid increase in the use of groundwater for irrigation \citep{}. \\

The canal network is extensive but has suffered from a lack of maintenance in recent decades \citep{}. Farmers perceive the canal network to be unreliable and report that it is difficult to predict when water will be available. Proximity to a canal branch does not indicate that the farmer has access. Consequently, even farmers with access to the canal network often seek to install wells as an alternative source of irrigation water if the canal supply does not meet demand. This is particularly the case where canal water has to be pumped to the farmers land, in which case it is usually preferable to use the pump, an expensive asset, to abstract groundwater instead. Nevertheless, the canal system, which is mostly unlined \citep{}, benefits farmers by contributing to recharge through leakage, which is estimated to be between X-Y\% \citep{}. \\

Flood irrigation is the most prevalent method of applying irrigation water to crops. Farmers tend to apply irrigation at set intervals during the growing season, with the schedule informed by a combination of experience and government and seed company recommendations \citep{}. This method contrasts with soil moisture based approaches (whereby irrigation is applied whenever the soil moisture falls below some threshold, which is usually based on field capacity) commonly employed in regional water use models \citep[e.g.][]{}. \\

The majority of farms in the region belong to smallholders, with the average farm size estimated to be X Ha. Smallholder agriculture dominates. ``A typical smallholder farm can be described as a household in which mainly the family labor is used and for which the farm provides a principal source of income'' \citep{cornish_???_1998,morton_impact_2007}. ``Such farmers are assumed to practice subsistence-oriented activities (Dercon, 2009) that are a mix of farming and labor sale, where the majority of labor is provided by the smallholder's household'' \citep{pande_sociohydrological_2016}. Decreasing farm size, an increase in food demand, and the availability of water for irrigation means that the practice of growing multiple crops over the course of the year has become a viable strategy for farmers to ensure their food security and profitability \citep{}. The rice-wheat rotation, whereby rice is grown during the \textit{kharif} season and wheat during \textit{rabi}, is most pervasive but crop selection is an important factor that farmers may employ to adapt to specific socioeconomic or biophysical conditions \citep{}. Intensive agricultural practices [and crop selection] have led to declining soil fertility across the region \citep{}, forcing farmers to increase their use of chemical fertiliser (Figure X). The problem is most acute amongst smallholder farmers who cannot afford the short-term loss in productivity associated with the introduction of a fallow period \citep{}. Consequently the area of fallow land across the Indo-Gangetic Plain is in decline \citep{}, and farmers report that fertiliser costs make up a substantial portion of their annual expenditure. \\

