\subsection{Irrigation supply}
The reliability of the canal network is an important influence on farm-level water management decisions \citep{okeeffe_including_2018}. In general, the reliability of the canal network is related to the distance from the canal head, with farmers near the head receiving a more reliable service, and farmers near the tail receiving a less reliable service \citep{}. We assume that farmers initially attempt to meet the irrigation demand from this source, such that the irrigation supply from the canal system is computed as

\begin{equation}
  I_{c}(t) =
  \begin{cases}
    I_{t}(t), & \text{if}\ I_{t}(t) \leq q_{c}(t)\\
    q_{c}(t), & \text{otherwise}.
  \end{cases}  
\end{equation}

\noindent where $q_{c}$ is the canal supply ($\mathrm{L T^{-1}}$). The irrigation water demand is subsequently removed from the canal (TODO, after Chris writes canal model section).\\

If farmers do not have access to the canal network, or if the canal does not contain sufficient water to meet the irrigation demand, we assume that farmers seek to exploit the groundwater resource. The maximum quantity of water which can be abstracted from a single tubewell is governed by the empirical equation of \cite{}, expressed

\begin{equation}
  Q_{w}(t) = \frac{t_{w} \times 129574.1 \times BHP}{d + ((255.5998 \times BHP^2) / (d^2 \times D^4))}
\end{equation}

% TODO: sort out units
\noindent where $Q_{w}(t)$ is well discharge in litres ($\mathrm{M T^{-1}}$), $t_{w}$ is the duration of the irrigation event in hours ($\mathrm{T}$), $BHP$ is the horsepower of the pump ($\mathrm{}$), $d$ is the average depth of the well in metres ($\mathrm{L}$), and $D$ is the diameter of the suction pipe in inches ($\mathrm{
L}$).\\

Hence, the demand for groundwater is expressed

\begin{equation}
  I_{g}(t) = I_{total}(t) - I_{c}(t)
  \begin{cases}
    I_{total}(t) - I_{c}(t), & \text{if}\ I_{total}(t) - I_{c}(t) \leq Q_{w}(t)\\
    Q_{w}(t), & \text{otherwise}.
  \end{cases}    
\end{equation}

\noindent and the total irrigation supply is

\begin{equation}
  I_{s}(t) = I_{c}(t) + I_{w}(t)
\end{equation}

\noindent The daily irrigation demand deficit is computed by subtracting the irrigation supply from the irrigation demand. This is accumulated during the growing season and used in the farm economics module to inform decisions about potential investments.\\

\subsection{Crop production}
Crop yield is estimated using the equation set out by \citet{doorenbos_???_1979}:

\begin{equation}
\left(1-\frac{Y_{a}(T)}{Y_{x}(T)}\right) = K_{y}\left(1-\frac{\sum\limits_{t=d_{s}}^{d_{h}} ET_{c}(t)}{\sum\limits_{t=d_{s}}^{d_{h}} ET_{x}(t)}\right)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $Y_{x}$ is maximum yield, $Y_{a}$ is actual yield, $K_{y}$ is the yield response factor, $ET_{x}$ is maximum evapotranspiration, $ET_{c}$ is actual crop evapotranspiration, $d_{s}$ is sowing day and $d_{h}$ is harvesting day. 

\subsection{Farm economics}
The farm economics module simulates farm-level economic activity based on physical and socioeconomic constraints. The module builds on the behaviour model described in \citet{okeeffe_including_2018} to represent a wider range of farm characteristics and to include specific adaptation measures encountered in the study region. \\

