\section{Numerical model}
Implicit in the research question is the need to model the heterogeneity... We therefore transferred the conceptual model to a distributed modelling framework with a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes. Subgrid heterogeneity is represented using the tiling approach adopted in many distributed hydrological and Earth system models \citep[e.g.][]{}. Accordingly, we represent the land surface in terms of three vegetated land covers (forest, grassland, and cropland) and two non-vegetated land covers (impervious land, water). The conceptual model outlined above is executed separately for each land cover type... parameters... We extend the tiled approach to account for two further levels of heterogeneity. We exploit this feature to include the farmer livelihood model. Cropland is further divided into subtypes representing individual crop types. ...further divided into a number of entities for which the livelihood model outlined above can be implemented separately. Figure X illustrates the way in which subgrid heterogeneity is considered. \\
% Somewhere we need to have some discussion of the merits of an ABM approach
% In this way, the model therefore implements an individual-based approach within each grid square ... see \citet{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. \\

The inclusion of farms effectively introduces another dimension to the model with size equal to the number of farms considered in each grid cell. Across the Indo-Gangetic Plain the average farm size is X Ha and cropland represents X \% of the land area. For a typical grid cell, therefore, a total of XYZ farms may be present. Clearly, therefore, it is both computationally and epistemologically infeasible to model each farm in the study region. On the other hand, simulations involving a random subset of farmers may have results which are significantly different to runs in which every farm is represented \citep{scheffer_super-individuals_1995}. These differnces may arise because outliers assume a greater influence on the overall response \citep{}. Similarly, changes in a single farm, such as the installation of a tubewell, may have a large effect on the aggregate results. Lastly, where random number generators are used to initialize variables, the value of the random seed may exert significant control on the simulation results \citep{scheffer_super-individuals_1995}. To overcome these challenges while maintaining computational efficiency we adopt the notion of a ``super-individual''; a concept used in ecology to efficiently model the behaviour of very large populations. A super-individual is a model object which is broadly considered as an individual but which in fact represents a group of \textit{n} individuals \citep{scheffer_super-individuals_1995}.\\

The selection of individuals from the population to be combined in a super-individual is based on defined characteristics of each individual \citep{scheffer_super-individuals_1995}. Here, we define the super-individuals, or super-farmers, on the basis of three key farm attributes: farm size, canal access, and number of tubewells per farm. In effect, therefore, we assume that farmers with a similar geographical location (represented by the position of the grid cell), a similar farm size, access to the same number of tubewells, and the same canal access status, may be treated as a single farm for the purpose of computing farmer livelihood using the model outlined above. \\

