\section{Model application}
We applied the model to the Gandak basin, a sub-basin of the Ganges basin in northern India which is representative of many water management issues encountered in the Indo-Gangetic Plain. The Gandak river originates in the Nepalese Himalaya, entering India at Triveni near Valmiki Nagar in the Pashchim Champaran district of Bihar. A large barrage on the India-Nepal border diverts flow into two large irrigation canal systems to the east and west of the river, respectively. A third canal system, slightly upstream of the barrage, enters a smaller canal system which serves Nepal. Downstream of the barrage, the Gandak river provides important ecosystem services. In particular, the river is an important habitat of two critically endangered, yet culturally important, riverine species: the Ganges River dolphin and the Gharial crocodile. \\

The barrage and its canal system supplies water to two irrigation command areas: the western branch canal supplies farmers in Nepal and Uttar Pradesh, while the eastern branch canal supplies farmers in Bihar. Barrage operations substantially affect boundary conditions of the Gandak basin; the release of water into the river for ecological flows and ecosystem services has a trade-off with respect to release of water into the canals. Despite the canal supply, the number of tubewells in the districts within the command area has increased dramatically in recent decades, in line with much of the rest of the Indo-Gangetic Plain, while the irrigated area supplied by canals has gradually fallen (Figure X). While groundwater levels in the Gandak basin are stable \citep{macdonald_groundwater_2016}, rural areas do not tend to have access to electricity and hence farmers typically rely on costly diesel pumps to abstract water for irrigation. \\

