\subsection{Scenario analysis}
% Following model calibration and validation, we use the modelling framework to ask specific questions of the coupled system. Firstly, we investigate its sensitivity to canal water availability... \\
We develop scenarios to explore the behaviour of the system by changing the model parameterisation to simulate potential policy interventions. A baseline scenario is established using the calibrated parameterisation. The first scenario represents a policy intervention to ensure the equitable distribution of canal water within the canal command area. District and village-level inventory data reveals an obvious gradient in canal access between the head and tail of the canal network (Figure). Since the allocation of water to the various canal networks are subject to national and international agreements, we assume that no more water can be diverted to the canal network. Instead, we attempt to improve the distribution by reducing canal leakage and forcing farmers situated in cells nearer the canal head take no more than their entitlement.
% Run model assuming that water in canal is divided equally across all cells supplied by the canal network (equitable), and assuming that cells nearer the head take more than their entitlement (non-equitable).

In the second scenario, we assume a canal operating policy which prioritises environmental flow in the Gandak river downstream of the barrage over irrigation demand. We specify a minimum environmental flow of X\% [could experiment with multiple percentages - 5\%, 10\% and 20\%, for example] of the discharge at the barrage must be released downstream. The remaining discharge is diverted to the east and west canal in proportion to the specified monthly requirements. 
 
